00:42:09.380 --> 00:42:11.600
And this Sambor is all
the way on the other side.

00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:14.630
This is northeast of Phnom Penh.

00:42:14.630 --> 00:42:16.599
And the other one is northwest.

00:42:16.599 --> 00:42:17.890
But they're both called Sambor.

00:42:17.890 --> 00:42:20.840
One is Sambor something
else, and this

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:22.740
is Sambor on the Mekong.

00:42:22.740 --> 00:42:25.460
The other one is Sambor Prei
Kuk, and this is Sambor Mekong.

00:42:25.460 --> 00:42:27.280
And they're both
seventh century.

00:42:27.280 --> 00:42:29.990
So the style is very well known.

00:42:29.990 --> 00:42:31.860
The artistic style
of everything,

00:42:31.860 --> 00:42:33.621
so we know it's seventh century.

00:42:33.621 --> 00:42:34.454
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:34.454 --> 00:42:36.791
AMIR ACZEL: Sure.

00:42:36.791 --> 00:42:39.290
AUDIENCE: I had originally had
the same question about this,

00:42:39.290 --> 00:42:41.319
and that other inscription
in India, right?

00:42:41.319 --> 00:42:43.110
How do you know somebody
didn't scribble it

00:42:43.110 --> 00:42:45.490
into the temple
walls later, right?

00:42:45.490 --> 00:42:51.460
But the other question I had
was is there any use of it

00:42:51.460 --> 00:42:56.100
in arithmetic at some
point in old Khmer?

00:42:59.480 --> 00:43:01.630
AMIR ACZEL: We don't know.

00:43:01.630 --> 00:43:04.080
In terms of the old Khmer,
this is all we have.

00:43:04.080 --> 00:43:08.940
So we have no knowledge
about their arithmetic.

00:43:08.940 --> 00:43:10.987
It would be very
interesting to find out.

00:43:10.987 --> 00:43:11.820
This is all we have.

00:43:11.820 --> 00:43:14.940
That's just one number.

00:43:14.940 --> 00:43:18.880
Well, we know some things, which
are actually very interesting.

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:20.182
So Coedes was an amazing guy.

00:43:20.182 --> 00:43:21.557
He wasn't a
mathematician at all,

00:43:21.557 --> 00:43:23.580
but he was fascinated
by mathematics.

00:43:23.580 --> 00:43:27.420
I don't remember the
exact way it works.

00:43:27.420 --> 00:43:34.440
But numbers in the east
were often given names.

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:37.330
So you'd say, the veda,
and there are four vedas.

00:43:37.330 --> 00:43:38.850
So the number four is veda.

00:43:38.850 --> 00:43:41.530
You say veda, it means four.

00:43:41.530 --> 00:43:44.860
Eyes means two, obviously.

00:43:44.860 --> 00:43:48.490
And census, I think, is
five, or something like that.

00:43:48.490 --> 00:43:50.501
And flavors is six.

00:43:50.501 --> 00:43:51.500
I may be confusing them.

00:43:51.500 --> 00:43:57.660
But every number of the
first few numbers has a word.

00:43:57.660 --> 00:43:59.200
And it's like a code.

00:43:59.200 --> 00:44:02.820
And you'd say, I'll
meet you at-- I

00:44:02.820 --> 00:44:07.450
don't know-- a particular
street, veda eyes census,

00:44:07.450 --> 00:44:09.150
and you know
exactly where it is.

00:44:09.150 --> 00:44:12.830
And he traces that, how they
do arithmetic with that.

00:44:12.830 --> 00:44:18.440
That would be a good question,
whether eyes plus eyes

00:44:18.440 --> 00:44:19.740
would be whatever four is.

00:44:19.740 --> 00:44:20.530
Well, veda.

00:44:20.530 --> 00:44:22.640
Veda is eyes plus
eyes, or eyes square.

00:44:22.640 --> 00:44:25.490
So I don't know if they
did arithmetic that way.

00:44:25.490 --> 00:44:28.580
Coedes started and
made a lot of progress.

00:44:28.580 --> 00:44:29.354
But it stopped.

00:44:29.354 --> 00:44:30.020
We know nothing.

00:44:30.020 --> 00:44:33.440
There are thousands
of steles in Cambodia.

00:44:33.440 --> 00:44:37.540
You go to museums, and they
have them in their store rooms.

00:44:37.540 --> 00:44:39.700
And he was a genius.

00:44:39.700 --> 00:44:41.020
He was just able to translate.

00:44:41.020 --> 00:44:42.390
He did 2,000 of them.

00:44:42.390 --> 00:44:43.010
And that's it.

00:44:43.010 --> 00:44:44.290
Nobody knows.

00:44:44.290 --> 00:44:50.190
Nobody has consistently
studied these further.

00:44:50.190 --> 00:44:50.890
Why?

00:44:50.890 --> 00:44:51.690
I have no idea.

00:44:51.690 --> 00:44:54.230
Maybe they just
have no resources.

00:44:54.230 --> 00:44:55.840
I guess I do know why.

00:44:55.840 --> 00:44:57.840
You don't want to
justify colonialism.

00:44:57.840 --> 00:45:04.894
But France says resources, and
Coedes wasn't just by himself.

00:45:04.894 --> 00:45:08.190
The was the Ecole
Francais d'Extreme Orient,

00:45:08.190 --> 00:45:13.800
which is the French School
of the Far East, I guess,

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:16.070
the extreme Orient.

00:45:16.070 --> 00:45:21.830
And they had a lot of money,
and they could do things.

00:45:21.830 --> 00:45:23.500
That's why they
were able to do it.

00:45:23.500 --> 00:45:25.020
Now, the Cambodians
go to Palermo

00:45:25.020 --> 00:45:28.640
to get somebody to teach them
how to restore artifacts.

00:45:28.640 --> 00:45:31.250
So I think that's
where the problem lies.

00:45:31.250 --> 00:45:32.950
Somebody needs
to-- there are tons

00:45:32.950 --> 00:45:34.950
of these things that
need to be translated.

00:45:34.950 --> 00:45:38.270
This is one of only
2,000, 3,000 inscriptions

00:45:38.270 --> 00:45:39.650
that have been translated.

00:45:39.650 --> 00:45:41.810
And there are
probably-- well, I don't

00:45:41.810 --> 00:45:43.310
know how many there
are in Cambodia.

00:45:43.310 --> 00:45:45.109
In India, there are millions.

00:45:45.109 --> 00:45:46.650
And they still need
to be translated.

00:45:46.650 --> 00:45:49.300
The problem with the
dating, again, a few of you

00:45:49.300 --> 00:45:52.070
alluded to is how do we
know that it's the date?

00:45:52.070 --> 00:45:53.510
That's a huge problem in India.

00:45:53.510 --> 00:45:57.010
So in India, the dates
are very, very murky.

00:45:57.010 --> 00:46:02.110
And the reason is that many
of the inscriptions in India

00:46:02.110 --> 00:46:04.820
are on copper plates.

00:46:04.820 --> 00:46:08.020
And the date is always on the
side, or often on the side.

00:46:08.020 --> 00:46:12.010
And you don't know if it was
added five centuries later

00:46:12.010 --> 00:46:14.030
or whatever.

00:46:14.030 --> 00:46:15.890
So the dates are very fishy.

00:46:15.890 --> 00:46:19.260
And that allows somebody
like Raju to claim,

00:46:19.260 --> 00:46:20.930
we invented everything.

00:46:20.930 --> 00:46:24.730
On the other hand, they probably
did have a lot of science,

00:46:24.730 --> 00:46:27.780
astronomy in particular,
and a lot of mathematics

00:46:27.780 --> 00:46:28.777
that they did develop.

00:46:28.777 --> 00:46:29.610
But it's all hidden.

00:46:29.610 --> 00:46:31.370
Nobody has translated
these things.

00:46:31.370 --> 00:46:35.400
And nobody knows the
dates with precision.

00:46:35.400 --> 00:46:38.360
Here, we are lucky.

00:46:38.360 --> 00:46:41.220
The good thing is
that it's in stone.

00:46:41.220 --> 00:46:44.360
It looks like it
hasn't been-- doesn't

00:46:44.360 --> 00:46:47.350
look to me like somebody
could have come in 1932

00:46:47.350 --> 00:46:49.900
and chiseled that 605.

00:46:49.900 --> 00:46:52.260
There are forgeries.

00:46:52.260 --> 00:46:54.810
I studied one of them,
a very interesting one.

00:46:54.810 --> 00:46:59.380
Maybe you know that story about
the Drake Plate in California.

00:46:59.380 --> 00:47:01.830
Many years-- it was discovered
by a Professor at Berkeley.

00:47:01.830 --> 00:47:04.430
And it was in the trunk of
his car for several years.

00:47:04.430 --> 00:47:07.200
And this is Francis
Drake put this plate here

00:47:07.200 --> 00:47:11.530
on the California coast,
commemorating his arrival there

00:47:11.530 --> 00:47:13.920
by Point Reyes Peninsula.

00:47:13.920 --> 00:47:15.270
And they found it was fake.

00:47:15.270 --> 00:47:19.330
The copper was made
using modern techniques.

00:47:19.330 --> 00:47:23.490
And the script wasn't
Elizabethan at all.

00:47:23.490 --> 00:47:24.880
It was forgery.

00:47:24.880 --> 00:47:26.100
So there are forgeries.

00:47:26.100 --> 00:47:29.110
There are lots of people
who have an incentive

00:47:29.110 --> 00:47:30.680
to forge things.

00:47:30.680 --> 00:47:33.390
And so this, you never know.

00:47:33.390 --> 00:47:34.750
I don't think this is fake.

00:47:34.750 --> 00:47:38.670
And the cool thing is
that we have that date.

00:47:38.670 --> 00:47:40.360
And it happens to have a zero.

00:47:40.360 --> 00:47:44.650
And the same, in India,
the Gwalior zero is 270.

00:47:44.650 --> 00:47:46.840
And it looks just
like our numerals,

00:47:46.840 --> 00:47:49.510
even though it's ninth century.

00:47:49.510 --> 00:47:51.250
The two looks like that.

00:47:51.250 --> 00:47:53.160
It's a very overdone two.

00:47:53.160 --> 00:47:55.340
And the zero is a circle.

00:47:55.340 --> 00:48:00.130
I'm sorry, the seven
actually goes back very far.

00:48:00.130 --> 00:48:02.630
The seven is one of
the first numerals that

00:48:02.630 --> 00:48:08.290
remained the same from its
inception, whatever that means.

00:48:08.290 --> 00:48:11.610
I've looked at a lot of
these scripts in India.

00:48:11.610 --> 00:48:15.900
There's Brahmi
numerals, and Ashoka

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:19.350
was a Buddhist king in
India, first few centuries.

00:48:19.350 --> 00:48:22.350
And he had pillars
all over India-- maybe

00:48:22.350 --> 00:48:24.130
you know-- they're
very famous pillars.

00:48:24.130 --> 00:48:26.130
And there are numerals
on them, and the numerals

00:48:26.130 --> 00:48:27.706
are called Ashoka numerals.

00:48:27.706 --> 00:48:29.080
Both Ashoka
numerals, and there's

00:48:29.080 --> 00:48:35.650
a Naneghat cave in the Western
Ghats, southeast of Mumbai.

00:48:35.650 --> 00:48:36.660
And you can go up there.

00:48:36.660 --> 00:48:38.070
It's a long hike to the top.

00:48:38.070 --> 00:48:41.399
There are numerals there called
the Naneghat inscription.

00:48:41.399 --> 00:48:42.940
So there are these
three scripts that

00:48:42.940 --> 00:48:46.556
go back the first few centuries,
two, three centuries AD.

00:48:46.556 --> 00:48:47.930
They're all around
the same time.

00:48:47.930 --> 00:48:49.850
I think Ashoka is about
the third century,

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:51.340
or maybe it's 300 or so.

00:48:51.340 --> 00:48:55.310
So all three of them have a
seven that's just like ours,

00:48:55.310 --> 00:48:59.040
without the-- just a
seven the way we write it,

00:48:59.040 --> 00:49:01.850
not the way European
write it, crossing it.

00:49:01.850 --> 00:49:07.260
So the seven is one of the first
numerals that just traveled

00:49:07.260 --> 00:49:10.920
through time to us
exactly as it is.

00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:12.970
So you have the
seven, and then you

00:49:12.970 --> 00:49:15.740
have a zero in India,
the Gwalior zero.

00:49:15.740 --> 00:49:17.240
Now, there's another
way-- there are

00:49:17.240 --> 00:49:20.710
many ways of dating things
that can authenticate them

00:49:20.710 --> 00:49:21.944
quite well.

00:49:21.944 --> 00:49:23.360
I'll get to you
in a second-- that

00:49:23.360 --> 00:49:25.670
can authenticate
them quite well.

00:49:25.670 --> 00:49:26.840
This is one example.

00:49:26.840 --> 00:49:32.820
It's not unique,
but it's very clear.

00:49:32.820 --> 00:49:33.620
You have a date.

00:49:33.620 --> 00:49:35.440
It has a zero in it.

00:49:35.440 --> 00:49:38.050
And you know when
that dynasty started.

00:49:38.050 --> 00:49:42.650
That dynasty started in
78, so we know the date.

00:49:42.650 --> 00:49:44.440
When you go earlier
in history, there's

00:49:44.440 --> 00:49:46.670
something very interesting
that can be done,

00:49:46.670 --> 00:49:50.530
and that is early civilizations
like the Babylonians were

00:49:50.530 --> 00:49:53.440
very careful in recording
total solar eclipses.

00:49:53.440 --> 00:50:00.580
They were very obsessed with
Venus and not the phases,

00:50:00.580 --> 00:50:03.890
they couldn't see them,
but the motions of Venus

00:50:03.890 --> 00:50:07.580
when it rises with
the sun and so on.

00:50:07.580 --> 00:50:11.780
And they also were interested
in total solar eclipses.

00:50:11.780 --> 00:50:14.220
So they tell you
something happened.

00:50:14.220 --> 00:50:17.910
The king died, whatever
king died on the day of,

00:50:17.910 --> 00:50:20.920
or five days after the
total solar eclipse.

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:24.040
You can find it exactly because
you use modern astronomy.

00:50:24.040 --> 00:50:26.010
You go back in time
roughly, and you

00:50:26.010 --> 00:50:30.370
know where the eclipse
path past on a certain time

00:50:30.370 --> 00:50:32.480
on a certain day
in a certain year.

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:34.230
And that has been
used, actually,

00:50:34.230 --> 00:50:38.430
to establish a lot of Assyrian,
Babylonian chronology.

00:50:38.430 --> 00:50:40.630
So that's another very
nice modern method.

00:50:40.630 --> 00:50:44.550
And of course,
radiocarbon is unbeatable.

00:50:44.550 --> 00:50:48.270
I've worked a little,
devised a statistical routine

00:50:48.270 --> 00:50:52.690
for making radiocarbon more
precise using the bootstrap.

00:50:52.690 --> 00:50:55.460
And the radiocarbon
is now, I don't know,

00:50:55.460 --> 00:50:57.760
50 years or within
a few centuries.

00:50:57.760 --> 00:50:59.450
So it's very accurate.

00:50:59.450 --> 00:51:02.380
AUDIENCE: Would you speak to the
difference between the numeral

00:51:02.380 --> 00:51:05.340
zero and the number zero?

00:51:05.340 --> 00:51:08.350
In particular, I'm
thinking imagining

00:51:08.350 --> 00:51:10.750
a record of an
inventory that might

00:51:10.750 --> 00:51:14.740
say, number of bushels
of wheat, zero.

00:51:14.740 --> 00:51:18.300
Number of jars of
wine, zero, which

00:51:18.300 --> 00:51:22.560
is distinct from the use of
the numeral as a placeholder.

00:51:22.560 --> 00:51:26.280
But the numeral to
represent the number zero.

00:51:26.280 --> 00:51:27.030
AMIR ACZEL: Right.

00:51:27.030 --> 00:51:32.320
So the way I understand it, that
is a sophisticated idea, too.

00:51:32.320 --> 00:51:36.380
In the west, at least, it was
difficult for people to say,

00:51:36.380 --> 00:51:40.590
we have zero
bottles of wine left

00:51:40.590 --> 00:51:44.020
for the holiday, or
something like that.

00:51:44.020 --> 00:51:51.240
And my understanding is that the
double-- what do you call it?

00:51:51.240 --> 00:51:56.420
The bookkeeping method,
double entry bookkeeping

00:51:56.420 --> 00:52:02.310
evolved because of that
inability to say there's zero.

00:52:02.310 --> 00:52:05.250
So you have numbers
of one kind here

00:52:05.250 --> 00:52:06.940
and numbers of the
other kind there.

00:52:06.940 --> 00:52:10.570
What you owe, what you
are owed, and so on.

00:52:13.350 --> 00:52:17.310
Yeah, it takes a little
sophistication to say,

00:52:17.310 --> 00:52:20.720
we have zero of something.

00:52:20.720 --> 00:52:22.530
Negative numbers are even worse.

00:52:22.530 --> 00:52:24.470
What do negative numbers mean?

00:52:24.470 --> 00:52:26.890
So when you study mathematics
and you look at the numbers,

00:52:26.890 --> 00:52:30.750
how they evolved, the idea of
numbers, how we perceive them,

00:52:30.750 --> 00:52:33.796
the positive, the natural
numbers and natural to us.

00:52:33.796 --> 00:52:36.295
One, two, three, four, five,
even if they go on to infinity.

00:52:38.940 --> 00:52:43.120
In order to define the negative
numbers, you need a zero.

00:52:43.120 --> 00:52:45.250
Because the zero is
the point of symmetry

00:52:45.250 --> 00:52:49.270
where the natural numbers
go to the right, and then

00:52:49.270 --> 00:52:50.680
the negative ones
go to the left.

00:52:50.680 --> 00:52:56.310
And you can have a
group under addition

00:52:56.310 --> 00:52:59.100
where you have the inverse
is the minute you have

00:52:59.100 --> 00:53:01.020
the negative numbers,
and you have a zero.

00:53:01.020 --> 00:53:04.210
So the zero is the
additive identity.

00:53:04.210 --> 00:53:06.520
The multiplicative
identity would be one.

00:53:06.520 --> 00:53:08.630
So then you can have a field.

00:53:08.630 --> 00:53:13.180
So yes, it's a
sophisticated idea.

00:53:13.180 --> 00:53:15.770
It was slow in the west.

00:53:15.770 --> 00:53:17.290
I don't know, in
the east, it seems

00:53:17.290 --> 00:53:21.110
to have been more
natural, maybe.

00:53:21.110 --> 00:53:24.910
I feel, and I have no
strong proof of that,

00:53:24.910 --> 00:53:30.780
and infinity also is an
idea that was maybe easier

00:53:30.780 --> 00:53:33.630
to evolve in the east, just
having read a lot of stuff

00:53:33.630 --> 00:53:35.970
about the east.

00:53:35.970 --> 00:53:41.050
In Hinduism, there's an
infinite sea, and the sea turtle

00:53:41.050 --> 00:53:47.850
on which Vishnu lies when
Brahma springs out of his navel.

00:53:47.850 --> 00:53:50.250
It's called Ananta,
which means infinity.

00:53:50.250 --> 00:53:52.140
So there are ideas of infinity.

00:53:52.140 --> 00:53:53.520
They didn't understand them.

00:53:53.520 --> 00:53:57.510
But they could talk about them
maybe more than in the west.

00:53:57.510 --> 00:54:00.370
Because Augustine writes
about the infinitude of God

00:54:00.370 --> 00:54:01.990
in certain ways.

00:54:01.990 --> 00:54:03.640
So infinity as well-- yeah?

00:54:07.410 --> 00:54:12.060
AUDIENCE: In the system
where the designation is just

00:54:12.060 --> 00:54:19.400
a blank space, like 60 is 6,
or 601 is 6, blank space, 1,

00:54:19.400 --> 00:54:23.280
how would you judge when
there's more than one space?

00:54:23.280 --> 00:54:27.310
And if there's more than
one, is it two or three?

00:54:27.310 --> 00:54:30.160
In order to really do
that with any accuracy,

00:54:30.160 --> 00:54:35.510
you need something in there,
a little jot of some kind.

00:54:35.510 --> 00:54:37.840
AUDIENCE: Or it could
be clear columns.

00:54:37.840 --> 00:54:39.482
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:54:39.482 --> 00:54:40.940
AMIR ACZEL: Good
point, good point.

00:54:40.940 --> 00:54:43.532
That's why the zero
is so important.

00:54:43.532 --> 00:54:45.240
You don't know how
many blanks are there.

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:46.820
And the blanks
also, remember, they

00:54:46.820 --> 00:54:49.310
didn't have anything
standardized

00:54:49.310 --> 00:54:55.350
like you'd print on a page,
and a blank is an exact width.

00:54:55.350 --> 00:54:57.206
This was written by
hand, or chiseled.

00:54:57.206 --> 00:54:59.080
And how do you know if
there's a blank there,

00:54:59.080 --> 00:55:03.430
or just the guy couldn't
judge distances very well?

00:55:03.430 --> 00:55:05.560
Especially if the
distances vary,

00:55:05.560 --> 00:55:08.560
there's no way to tell where
there's a blank unless it's

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:11.220
really a significant width.

00:55:11.220 --> 00:55:12.300
So that's a good point.

00:55:12.300 --> 00:55:14.580
But you could-- going back
to your previous question,

00:55:14.580 --> 00:55:18.960
you could assume-- and
what somebody else asked,

00:55:18.960 --> 00:55:24.750
too, and commented on-- a
blank could be quite rationally

00:55:24.750 --> 00:55:26.400
a void.

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:28.910
And maybe it's
not that Buddhist.

00:55:28.910 --> 00:55:32.870
Maybe it's an idea
that came other ways.

00:55:32.870 --> 00:55:34.680
Going back to infinity,
infinity really

00:55:34.680 --> 00:55:40.270
was understood with the work of
Cantor in the 1800s in Germany.

00:55:40.270 --> 00:55:45.300
So infinity really becomes
a mathematical concept

00:55:45.300 --> 00:55:47.180
in the late 1800s.

00:55:47.180 --> 00:55:49.490
But maybe what I'm
trying to say is

00:55:49.490 --> 00:55:52.100
that eastern people
talked more about infinity

00:55:52.100 --> 00:55:53.630
than people in the west.

00:55:53.630 --> 00:55:55.520
Yeah?

00:55:55.520 --> 00:55:58.740
AUDIENCE: Just on the subject
of multiple zeroes in a row,

00:55:58.740 --> 00:56:05.170
I'm trying to remember
the tables of chords

00:56:05.170 --> 00:56:09.180
in Ptolemy's Almagest, which
is second century AD, right?

00:56:09.180 --> 00:56:13.510
Which has trigonometric
functions of every half degree

00:56:13.510 --> 00:56:16.104
value between 0 and
whatever they went up to,

00:56:16.104 --> 00:56:17.520
30 degrees or
something like that,

00:56:17.520 --> 00:56:18.961
for trigonometric calculations.

00:56:18.961 --> 00:56:20.460
There's calculations
in the Almagest

00:56:20.460 --> 00:56:24.572
that certainly go out to like
five places in sexidecimal

00:56:24.572 --> 00:56:25.530
or something like that.

00:56:25.530 --> 00:56:27.460
So certainly, there
must been calculations

00:56:27.460 --> 00:56:29.080
that they were doing
at that time, all

00:56:29.080 --> 00:56:32.700
the trigonometric calculations
that they were doing

00:56:32.700 --> 00:56:34.617
that involved multiple
zeroes in a row.

00:56:34.617 --> 00:56:36.450
It seems very unlikely
that they would never

00:56:36.450 --> 00:56:40.780
have hit two adjacent base
60 slots that were empty.

00:56:40.780 --> 00:56:42.820
But of course, all
their calculations

00:56:42.820 --> 00:56:45.760
were done in very strict
tables, these tables

00:56:45.760 --> 00:56:48.955
of values of the
chord function had

00:56:48.955 --> 00:56:51.330
the firsts, and the seconds,
and thirds, and the fourths,

00:56:51.330 --> 00:56:54.282
and the fifths, which are
fractional powers of 60,

00:56:54.282 --> 00:56:55.490
all lined up with each other.

00:56:55.490 --> 00:56:58.859
So I don't know how Ptolemy
actually wrote it, though.

00:56:58.859 --> 00:56:59.900
AMIR ACZEL: You're right.

00:56:59.900 --> 00:57:01.651
If you're careful
with writing a table

00:57:01.651 --> 00:57:03.650
and there are five zeroes
that have to be there,

00:57:03.650 --> 00:57:07.020
so there are five blank columns,
or whatever, however they

00:57:07.020 --> 00:57:07.520
did it.

00:57:07.520 --> 00:57:08.490
That makes sense.

00:57:08.490 --> 00:57:08.990
Yes.

00:57:08.990 --> 00:57:10.730
So they must have
had a technology.

00:57:10.730 --> 00:57:12.690
So maybe ours is
more advanced just

00:57:12.690 --> 00:57:13.990
in the sense it's standardized.

00:57:13.990 --> 00:57:15.406
You have a zero,
so you don't have

00:57:15.406 --> 00:57:18.720
to worry about making
a table and columns.

00:57:18.720 --> 00:57:22.280
So the ideas must have
been there early on.

00:57:22.280 --> 00:57:27.070
But maybe they don't agree
with our sense of neatness

00:57:27.070 --> 00:57:30.020
and keeping things
much more universal.

00:57:30.020 --> 00:57:33.400
So you can write a number
here and read it in Japan,

00:57:33.400 --> 00:57:38.020
